segments.text: I want to mention something I want to make sure I covered.
Please do.
Over the, you know, the constant thing over the 30 or so years
has been teaching that one course and being a graduate advisor in the department.
So a lot of interaction with undergraduate and graduate students,
which I've enjoyed in both cases.
And I've been offered, I mean, I've been asked so many times,
how in the world do you keep teaching that same course for 30 years?
Well, that I don't know.
I don't really have an answer for that,
except it's different students every semester.
This is my last semester to do it this time,
and I've just as decided about doing it as I'd ever be.
It kind of feels funny.
You just can't imagine not continuing to do it, to tell you the truth.
But I've continued to enjoy it.
But I've always tried to, at least every couple of semesters,
do something different about the course.
Add something about putting, redoing audio tapes,
or now I've put all the objectives on the web.
Last semester I did that.
So something to keep me a little bit current.
And something also to use different visual aids.
And never to be too rigid in the lecture.
Always.
Kind of let it flow and cover things in a different order.
But in addition to that, I think in the university community,
there's so many opportunities to, I guess, be a servant or grow yourself.
And so over the years, I've advised student clubs.
Sometimes many as four at one time, but mainly I've always had at least one.
Advised core outfits.
Served as advisor to the political forum, student group,
shortly after that.
Got to meet Gerald Ford and a few other prominent people in those years.
And enjoyed the heck out of that.
Then served a couple of years on the MSC Consulate Directorate.
Had a different kind of experience.
Faculty senate in the department.
Said, you know, we need to have somebody from the department be on the faculty senate.
So I get, I mean, I didn't say anything to anybody.
I get nominated and I end up on the faculty senate.
And then.
Uh.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
Hold on a second.
So, Fred Smines over in Rainside said, well, it's a shame.
We're just going to let John McNermoth be the first speaker with no competition at all.
Somebody ought to run against him.
Wilford, you run against him.
Why, I did.
Well, of course.
Unfortunate, deservedly, John.
He's elected.
But John makes me the deputy.
And then, of course, this greases a wheel for me to be the speaker the next year.
But I'm keeping all my teaching duties and all my advice all at the same time.
But that was a, see, that was an outlet of different, and of course, the speaker year
was a, that was a tremendous experience to interact with all of the higher administrators
and that kind of deal.
And it was a, it was an exciting time for the senate trying to get established.
Did the senate, did the senate come up with any recommendation that you thought was a
little goofy that you still had as their voice to support?
Uh, I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't remember.
The only, and this happened actually after my year as speaker was over, the core curriculum
was being developed during that year, all that year.
And I'm not particularly proud of it, but I ended up in the final analysis voting against
the final adoption of the core curriculum.
Not because I opposed the core curriculum, but because there was always in the development
of it, there had been, I quote, a technological requirement anticipated in it.
And this got washed out at the end.
And I, I felt so strongly about that that I ended up voting no.
And I didn't feel real good about that.
But I didn't have to promote that to the senate.
I, no, I don't remember anything.
I'm trying to remember.
It had something to do with women's program or something.
Gosh, I don't know if I have any notes about this or not.
But Dr. Vandenberg called me into his office.
And he was mad as a hornet.
I mean, he was off the wall for just two or three minutes.
Then he calmed down and we had a good conversation.
But I, it was, it was something about the women's program.
I think something that Ms. Schaffer, that Dr. Schaffer was the woman in charge of the
women's committee program.
I don't, I don't remember the particulars.
But I do remember Dr. Vandenberg, he was mightily upset when the first one in.
But he calmed down.
He calmed down.
What do you think?
But, but I did that.
And then I became a continuous improvement facilitator.
Let's stay, let's stay with faculty senate just a second.
What do you think the faculty's role in decision making for this institution?
Ought to be?
You know, I'm kind of comfortable with the senate being in an advisory role.
I, I don't, I don't, I'm not one of those that quote thinks the faculty needs to make
all the decisions.
Because I don't, the faculty is just one component in the whole university community.
And the, and the university president ultimately, yeah, an organized venue by which the faculty
can make its decisions.
To make its feelings known.
And I think on matters of academics, it's, I would hope, I would hope that the president,
and I think all of them have, tended to support senate decisions.
There have been exceptions, I guess, but.
In the department, should there be a department head or a department chairman?
For, for department lock hours with a three agency deal and, and responsibilities, you
know.
I think the one thing that he's got to be careful about is the faculty.
As far as the public is concerned.
I think the public is very, very concerned about the faculty's role in this institution.
And I think if the faculty is out of state and in state, I think it needs to be a head.
On Wednesday, whether or not they qualified or not, uh.

Kept getting earlier and earlier.
You had to turn in senior grades.
And it came first.

And I guess I did, I guess I did, we did, we did 25 percent seniors.

It worked back three or four days.
Oh, so it got earlier and earlier.
It kept getting earlier and earlier.
You had to turn in senior grades.
And it came fast, because seniors were just, I mean,
I taught a big class that would have 25% seniors.
And I guess I did begin to get a little chapped about them
not taking finals, because they would put off classes
like mine for the last semester.
So they didn't have to take my finals.
Of all of those services, which ones
were the most satisfying to you, as you look back?
Each one while I was doing it.
I wouldn't want to pick one.
I guess the most different, of course,
was being speaker at the faculty center for a year.
Maybe that was the hideous kind of a deal.
Get your tickets to the Texas game in Austin.
We won.
A few things like that I remember very well.
But.
Yeah.
No, in the early days, being an advisor to a corps outfit,
having come through the corps, there
were a lot of good experiences associated with that.
How do you feel about the corps as you look back on it now?
How do you feel about the corps today?
Much more military than it was then.
Is it better or worse?
Plus, minus?
I haven't had real close contact in recent years,
not to see much on the inside.
I think it's been about, yeah, many more people,
I guess you could say, many more people in the corps who really
have a kind of a pro-military posture.
See, when I came through the corps, many of us were there
because we had to be there.
It was either being in the corps or being in Korea.
Yeah.
The corps was preferable.
It was preferable.
So you had a major, major influence in the corps of people
who were, yeah, we could kind of tolerate the bull
and that kind of stuff and enjoy some of it,
but we never had any dream about being a military somebody.
I feel like there's been more, I think a lot of that's been,
maybe gotten rid of in recent years,
but I feel like there's been a lot more of what artists call
really cheap stuff.
During all those years, describe a typical week for you
during the academic year.
You started at Monday and did what and how long and so forth.
Take a thorough week.
How many nights were you busy and so forth?
Well, with all of the kind of extracurricular activities and things I've had,
there were probably not very many nights when I didn't have a meeting or do something at
home.
I've been a bicycle rider for a long time.
I've normally, and I like to get here on the bicycle before the traffic gets too bad,
and I'm normally not going home until it's not too bad again.
So I've typically been at work from 7.30, 7.45 in the morning until 5.30 or 6 in the
afternoon and usually bring lunch.
We have a big lunch.
We have a big lunch.
a bridge playing group here, lunch, but during the school year, most of the time, I had an
8 o'clock class on Monday, Wednesday, Friday.
So you have to get here early to be ready
to go for that.
And I've had 1130 for many years now, 1130 to 1220 class.
So even for
the bridge playing group, that cuts you lunch hours.
Now what was this second class?
The same class.
Oh, same.
Two sections.
Two sections.
Okay.
And what did you tell your students that your office hours were for them to come
by?
You never had office hours.
The door was open.
I've always told them the door was open.
Call me.
Now it's email.
You're welcome
to come in any time you can catch me.
That's what I always said.
But I've never set rigid office hours.
How would you compare the quality of the students now?
Oh.
With the students when you first got here?
That's a hard read.
I suspect, I suspect the overall quality in terms of academic capability
is better.
In terms of maturity, in the sense of the student knowing who they are and what
they're about, it's not as good now as it was then.
Class attendance generally is much
poorer than it was in those days.
Students can't take nearly as heavy a load as they
used to, as I view it.
They have, I don't know how many of them spend their time, but
I mean I can visualize some of the options when you see them unload all the things they
have.
I mean there's TV, there's the internet, there's music, all of them have cars, they're
mobile, they leave here on weekends.
So, I just think there are a lot of competing things
that we can do.
So, I think it's a little bit more interesting to look at the quality of the students.
I don't know if you can do something about the quality of the students.
I mean I don't
know.
But, I don't know if you're going to get an A for students' attention.
I don't
see as much interest in learning as a general rule.
I just don't see as much interest in
learning.
In your.
I didn't get a degree, but I don't see much interest in learning.
In that course that you've been doing all these years, do you think you, your, how does
your grading system now, in other words, what does it take to make an A now compared to
then?
I'd like to tell you it hasn't changed much.
What?
but not nearly as many make A's now as they did then.
Is that right?
No, sir.
What about flunking?
Many more today.
Many more.
Many more.
Yeah, 1 to 3% in the early days.
It runs in the seven, six to 10 now.
I always thought I had to have at least 15% A's in class.
I mean, I felt bad if I didn't have at least 15% A's,
and lots of semesters I'd have over 50% A's and B's.
But not now.
About 35% A's and B's now most of the time.
It varies from semester to semester.
Last summer, this past summer,
but the summer before, I had a real good class,
but this past summer, terrible.
Now, this fall, looks like, I mean,
I had 142, I had 162 in class Monday.
Well, that's not bad.
What about women enrollment in the class now
compared to years ago?
Well, I've had some summer classes
with more women than men.
This semester, seems that my percentage of women
is quite a bit lower than it's been some time.
And I'm assuming far more urban kids now.
Oh yeah, for sure.
Many internationals in the undergraduate course?
Not many.
Probably 5% less.
I bet there are a lot more from broken homes
than there would have been 20 years ago.
I think that's the big change.
I think kids are about as honest as they've ever been.
I think the ability's there.
I think the maturity factor, in terms of them
feeling good about themselves, having a well-developed ethos,
code to live by.
I just think many of them are not there.
Do you have much indication of scholastic dishonesty now?
No, I wouldn't say, that's what I say.
I think they're better.
They're about as honest as they've ever been.
I don't see, I've had a little of that all along,
but I don't think they're any less honest.
I think, I've always said students tend to live up or down
to your expectations in that arena.
You have high expectations of them, in terms of honesty.
I think you generally get it.
How many students do you reckon you taught in that class?
I have a record down the stairs.
I don't think I made 18,000, but I'm close, between 17,500 and 18,000.
All right, now I'm getting near the end.
Among your departmental colleagues, to whom do you feel the greatest appreciation?
I'm not going to ask you the negative.
Which colleagues are you more grateful to?
Well, probably Larry Wilding, in terms of what a colleague has meant to me personally.
I think he's a great person.
He's a great person.
He's a great person.
I thought Larry was a great guy.
I thought he was a great guy.
I thought he was a great guy.
He's done an awful lot of things for me personally.
My own professional life.
I think a lot of people in the department would probably say that.
Larry's made us all better.
He's certainly been a strong plus for me, in some of the things I've been able to experience
and do.
Hank Mills was somebody I always have a lot of respect for.
He was a very different guy.
He had a master's degree.
Oh, he's Texas country boy.
But, yeah.
I guess in the early years, I had about as close association with him as anybody.
Some pretty good country wisdom there that he could impart.
He could read students.
He could read students.
You're inferring that he was a buddy?
Yeah, kind of.
Yeah.
Who's been your closest buddies, friends, in the department or elsewhere on the campus?
You know, I don't think I could say that I've been, I don't think I've singled on anybody
like that.
We have a departmental bridge group that gets together once a month, and so I guess you,
Larry and Gladys.
So, Larry and Gladys are probably, by virtue of church and department and everything, have
probably been closer to them.
They were quite close to the Runge's during their years here.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah.
I think Marcia was always close to Darce Darby, and Cedric Van Buechman lives down the street,
but I was never, you know, always liked to interact with Ron and Hans, but never, I've
never, I guess you'd have to say Larry, and yet we don't spend a lot of time together.
Alright, looking up in the hierarchy, to whom do you think you're most familiar with?
Who do you think, because of what they have meant to the institution, do you feel the
greatest gratitude at the college and at the institutional level?
Who's been, who did the most to make A&M better?
You think at the college?
Well, of course, I don't have that whole perception.
University, I'd have to say Earl Rutter.
Okay.
Because Earl Rutter was...
And it doesn't have to be just one, are there...
He was the man in the spot at the time.
I mean, he, he was the man in the spot at the time.
Yeah.
Yeah.
I mean, he, he obviously, his service here preceded me, but I, but I think he probably

Anybody?
In the college?
Mm-hmm.
I'm guessing that Patterson probably did as much to wake it up to what it could possibly
be, and that's more hearsay than any knowledge.
I've never done any very big study on that.
Okay.
Probably Harry Conkle.
He had strengths and weaknesses, but I think, I think I'd have to say Harry.
Okay.
Now...
The department, the department has to be Bloodworth, without a shadow of a doubt.
Let's make believe that you've been recruited now as the consultant to advise the department
and the college and the institution of what it should do in the future.
What would you advise the department, and the college, and the institution of what it
should do in the future?
What would you advise this department to do in the future?
I'm going to go at it the backward way a little bit.
Okay.
Institution.
I hope we don't lose sight of what it is that I think makes A&M unique in terms of can-do
attitude, friendliness, openness, that kind of thing.
And I think, I think some of those things that contribute most to making it what, I've
always said in my classes, you know, I've been to Wisconsin, I've been to Cornell, I've
been here.
I'm not about to tell you that Texas A&M is the best institution I've ever been associated
with, but I am going to tell you it's unique.
And I really believe it's unique.
And I, particularly what I consider the positive parts of that uniqueness, I hope we don't
lose.
And I don't think those, those points are going to help us be top ten.
I mean, I think if you get all wrapped up in being top ten, you know, you're going to
get all wrapped up in being top ten, we can lose, we can lose some things that, that
may not contribute to just being top ten, but make us unique in a desirable way.
So I hope as an institution we don't lose sight of that.
In a department, there obviously, there needs to be an ability to, to bring all areas along
in it.
Well, we're going to have to identify, probably to an extent we haven't done, we're going
to have to identify the areas where we want to be top flight and where we just want to
be, meet our, quote, academic responsibilities.
I don't think we can be, I don't think we can be everything to everybody.
And I think, I think at the college level, I think Ed Heiler has a, you know, that's
one of the things I kind of fault him on.
I think he, I think he's not.
He's not gotten beyond us thinking we'd be everything to everybody.
So we've not made some hard decisions there that we probably could make.
And we probably haven't made some hard ones in the department that we need to make.
The balance that, right now, in terms of grant dollars, the biotech, genetics, molecular
biology, they're, they're swinging a big stick.
I think there's a threat to the whole land grant system.
Stemming land.
Stemming out of this with an increased emphasis on patenting genes, on getting royalties that
goes back into plant breeders' and geneticists' pockets.
That an increasing percentage of the support to do the research is coming from soft money
sources.
There's not, there, there tends to be not nearly in new faculty the support that we
need.
There's not the sense of servanthood that I think befits people in colleges of agriculture
and land grant institutions.
We're losing some of that.
And it's causing, and maybe that's the biggest challenge I see in the department, is to maintain
that, that spirit of serving the taxpayers who make it possible for you to be here and
have such a, a high emphasis on feathering your own nest.
It tends to become more materialistic as a, as a faculty.
I don't like that.
Are there some, are there some specialties within this department's scope that you think
ought to get emphasis?
You said it can't be all things to all people.
Yeah.
Well, for the, for the major, for the major commodities in the state.
Grains are corn, cotton, small grains.
We need to maintain a continuity of expertise from the very base level to the top.
Because in many cases the market for the products is not sufficiently large that it's going
to attract the large seed companies.
And they're getting bigger all the time.
So they only want to do things that are super small.
Great.
